cal power, a force that could alter the fabric of reality. Studying these themes in Mark Twain’s writings, Bruce Michelson also provides a fascinating overview of technological changes that transformed the American printing and publishing industries during Twain's lifetime, changes that opened new possibilities for content, for speed of production, for the size and diversity of a potential audience, and for international fame. The story of Mark Twain’s life and art, amid this media revolution, is a story with powerful implications for our own time, as we ride another wave of radical change: for printed texts, authors, truth, and consciousness.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 29. Mai 2023) 0aAuthors and publisherszUnited StatesxHistoryy19th century. 0aPrinting in literature. 0aPrintingzUnited StatesxHistoryy19th century. 0aPublishers and publishingzUnited StatesxHistoryy19th century. 7aLITERARY CRITICISM / American / General.2bisacsh  aamerican publishing history.  aamericana.  aconsequences of a revolution.  acultural revolution.  aeasy to read.  aediting and publishing.  aengaging.  aepistemological.  aepistemology.  afamous american writers.  ahistorical.  ahistory of publishing.  ainternational fame.  alife changes.  alifetime.  alively.  amedia revolution.  ametaphysical power.  aprinting press.  apublishing and printing industry.  aradical change.  aretrospective.  atypesetting.  awood cutting.08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertUniversity of California Press Backlist Package 2000-2013z97831106904220 cprintz978052024759840uhttps://doi.org/10.1525/978052093284540uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780520932845423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9780520932845/original  a978-3-11-069042-2  University of California Press Backli